WHEN INCIDENT OCCURRED WE MADE ALL NOTIFICATIONS AND PULLED THE TRAILER OUT AND CLOSED IT UP.
UNLOADING BOX CAME APART SPILLING CONTENTS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT, CHEMTREC CALLED.  NEED IMPROVE PACKAGING BY SHIPPER.

POSSIBLE SOME LIQUID WAS ON TOP OF THE DRUM FROM THE SHIPPER PRIOR TO PICK UP. DRUM WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION.

column168: driver was unloading product into underground storage tank.  ust would not hold all product ordered and the ust vapor recovery system vents were not operating properly.  product backed up into unloading hose and fittings. driver asked usps employees to fuel a number of vehicles so he could empty his hoses.  after several vehicles had been fueled driver attempted to remove fitting from ust filling tube and product pressured back up through fill tube onto concrete driveway.  spilled product spread over an area of approximately 15' x 15' and was allowed to evaporate.

column168: ABOUT 10 GRAMS OF SODIUM AZIDE, WHITE POWDER, WAS FOUND AROUND ONE DRUM AND ON THE PLASTIC SHEET PLACED UNDER THE DRUMS. THEY WERE EXAMINED LATER AT THE MEDICAL CLINIC AND RELEASED.  WE NOTIFIED SF AIRPORT AUTHORITIES, FAA AND SF AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE REPRESENTATIVES OF ALL OF THE ABOVE AUTHORITIES WERE PRESENT AT OUR FACILITY TO OBSERVE THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION.  INTERNATIONAL TECHNOLOGY CORP OF SF (IT CORP) DISPOSED OF THE LEAKED SUBSTANCE, THE PLASTIC SHEET.  IT CORP. ALSO OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A LARGER FIBERBOARD DRUM AND RELEASED IT TO THIS COMPANY.

column168: ON MONDAY MARCH 25, 1991 MIKE HAYDEN OUR OS&D CLERK IN KCI CALLED TO REPORT A KCI CITY DRIVER (ROY PATTON) WAS COMPLAINING OF FUMES FROM A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER.  THIS WAS PRO 046488264 WHICH CONTAINED 3 PLTS OF 11 CARTONS FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS.  APPARENTLY THE BOX WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  BILL TOLLY THE DOCK WORKER IN KCI NOTICED A TEAR BUT DID NOT THINK THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING SO HE LOADED IT FOR DELIVERY.  AFTER THE FIRST STOP, THE DRIVER COMPLAINED OF FUMES, SO OUR REGIONAL SAFETY & SECURITY MANAGER WAS SENT TO THE SCENE.  THE TRUCK WAS RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL AND CITY DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO NORTH KANSAS CITY HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  WAS RELEASED THAT SAME AFTERNOON.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.  ALL UNDAMAGED FREIGHT WAS DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE AND DAMAGED TUBES RETURNED TO SHIPPER PER THEIR AUTHORIZATION IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

IN REGARDS TO A SPILL WHICH OCCURRED AT QUAKER OATS INC. AT DALLAS, TEXAS ON MARCH 05, 1991 HERE IS AN ACCOUNT OF THE INCIDENT, IN MY OWN WORDS: TRAINEE BARRY COHN AND MYSELF ARRIVED AT QUAKER OATS AT 10:45 AM.  WE LOCATED COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE WHO PROMPTLY ESTABLISHED TELEPHONE CONTACT WITH THE PROPER INDIVIDUAL (J.D. TOWNLEY) AND INSTRUCTED US WHERE TO WAIT FOR HIM.  WE WAITED UNTIL 12:40 PM., AT WHICH TIME J. D. TOWNLEY APPEARED AND SHOWED US WHERE TO BACK IN AND WHERE TO HOOK UP.  THEN J. D  TOWNELY LEFT AT THIS TIME, BARRY COHN TURNED THE TRUCK AROUND AND BACKED IT IN TO THE DESIGNATED AREA.  THEN WE SUITED UP, CHECKED THE WHEELS, THEN HOOKED UP THE AIR COMPRESSOR AND SEVENTY FEET OF PRODUCT HOSE AND WAITED FOR THE OKAY TO UNLOAD.  WHEN WE GOT THE OKAY TO UNLOAD AT 1:35 PM., WE BUILD UP AIR PRESSURE (12 LB.) AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD.  AT 2:20 PM A REPRESENTATIVE OF QUAKER OATS APPEARED AND INFORMED US THAT THE PRODUCT WAS FOAMING OUT OF THE CONTAINER.  WE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND WERE USHERED TO THE AREA WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS TO BE STORED.  THE AREA WAS COVERED WITH FOAM, INDICATING THAT IT HAD BEEN FOAMING FOR QUITE SOME TIME.  SO, WE WAITED FOR THE FOAM TO SUBSIDE.  WHEN IT DID, THE AREA INSIDE THEIR TRAINING WALL AROUND THE STORAGE TANK WAS FULL AND HAD OVERFLOWED INTO THE RETAINING AREA ADJACENT TO IT.  WE WERE THEN TOLD TO FINISH UNLOADING AND WAIT FOR A REPRESENTATIVE FROM B.C WILLIAMS INC. (BART ARREN) WHO WAS TO HELP US FIND THE SOLUTION TO CLEANING UP THE MESS.  WE FINISHED UNLOADING, SHUT DOWN, CLEANED AND PUT AWAY OUR EQUIPMENT, THEN WAITED FOR BART,  WHEN BART ARRIVED, IT WAS DETERMINED HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS LOST (APPROXIMATELY 175 GALLONS).  THEN WE ALL DISCUSSD THE PROBLEM AND POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS.  AFTER MUCH DISCUSSION AND SEVERAL PHONE CALLS, WE ALL AGREED THAT THE BEST SOLUTION WOULD BE TO PUMP THE LOST PRODUCT BACK INTO THE TRAILER AND RETURN IT TO B.C. WILLIAMS INC.  SO I CALLED OUR TERMINAL MANAGER (EDDIE WILLARD) AND RELATED ALL PRIOR EVENTS TO HIM AND TOLD HIM ABOUT THE FINAL DECISION. HE SENT US A PUMP AND 130 FEET OF PRODUCT HOSES APPROXIMATELY 5:00 PM AT WHICH TIME BARRY COHN, MIKE STOUT ND MYSELF HOOKED UP THE PUMP AND 200 FEET OF PRODUCT HOSE AND BEGAN PUMPING THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE RETAINING AREA BACK INTO THE TRAILER.  WHEN HE HAD PUMPED ALL WE COULD PUMP OUT OF THEIR TRAINING AREA, THERE WAS STILL APPROXIMATELY ONE INCH OF PRODUCT LEFT ON THE FLOOR.  A SUPERVISOR FOR QUAKER OATS (NAME UNKNOWN) EXAMINED THE AREA AND TOLD US HE WOULD TAKE CARE OF THE REST OF IT WITH HIS PUMP.  HE THANKED US FOR DOING WHAT HE COULD TO AID IN THE CLEAN UP PROCESS.  WE ALL SHOOK HANDS, THEN BARRY COHN, MIKE STOUT AND MYSELF CLEANED AND PUT AWAY OUR EQUIPMENT. THEN MIKE STOUT LEFT IN THE COMPANY PICKUP TO RETURN TO THE TERMINAL YARD.  AT THE SAME TIME (APPROXIMATELY 6:30 PM) BARRY COHN AND MYSELF LEFT QUAKER OATS HEADED FOR B.C  WILLIAMS INC.  THANK YOU PAUL FRYE, JR. PAUL FRYE WAS DISPATCHED ON A LOAD TO QUAKER OATES SHIPPER WA

column168: AFTER UNLOADING HIS LOAD THE DRIVER DRAINED THE TANK WAGON HOSES, COVERED THE ENDS WITH PLASTIC BAGS HELD IN PLACE BY RUBBER BANDS TO PREVENT LEAKAGE, AND THEN PLACED THEM IN THE HOSE TROUGH.  DUE TO WEATHER CONDITIONS (RAIN, ICE, SNOW) THE HOSE TROUGH BEGAN TO FILL WITH WATER WHICH ENTERED THE TANKWAGON HOSED AND BEGAN TO WASH THE ECOLINER FROM THE DIRTY HOSES.  TO PREVENT DIRTY WATER FROM LAEKING ON THE ROADWAY THE DRIVER PLUGGED THE DRAINAGE HOLE IN THE HOSE TROUGH.  THE EXCESS WATER THEN FROZE IN THE HOSE TROUGH.  UPON REACHING HIS DESTINATION THE DRIVER PARKED THE TANKWAGON IN A DESIGNATED PARKING LOT.  AFTER THE ICE IN THE HOSE TROUGH THAWED THE TANKWAGON WAS MOVED BY THE PLANT YARD SWITCHER AND THE DIRTY WATER SPLASHED OUT OF THE TROUGH ONTO THE ROAD WAY.  WITH THE USE OF FLOOR DRI THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY RHONE POULENC PERSONNEL.  IN THE FUTURE THE HOSE TROUGH WILL BE CHECKED PRIOR TO MOVING A TANKWAGON.

column168: AFTER PICKING UP A LOAD OF CRUDE OIL  FROTN THE LOCATION, THE DRIVER DROVE THE VEHICLE OFF THE LOCATION AND STARTED DOWN THE ROAD.  THE ROD WAS VERY MUDDY AND SLICK. THE PUP TRAILER SLID OFF THE ROAD AND TURNED OVER.  IT CAME TO REST ON IT'S SIGHT SIDE ON THE BANK OF DRY CREEK BED.  SOME ROCKS ALONG SIDE THE DRY CREEK BED PUNCTURED THE CARGO TANK WHEN IT LAYED OVER ON THEM.  105.72 BBLS OF CRUDE OIL ESCAPED OF WHICH WE WERE ABLE TO SALVAGE ALL BUT 64.5 BBLS.  THE FIRST THING THAT WAS DONE AFTER THE ACCIDENT WAS TO PLACE DIKES AHEAD OF THE SPILL AND CONTAIN IT TO AS SMALL AN AREA AS POSSIBLE.  THEN AFTER SETTING THE CARGO TANK PUP TRAILER UP AND TAKING IT AWAY FROM THE SCENE WE BEGAN VACUUMING UP THE SPILLED XXX CRUDE OIL WITH A VACUUM TRUCK AND WAS ABLE TO VACUUM UP 41.22 BBLS.  THE REMAINING CRUDE OIL CAUGHT ON FIRE.  VIRTUALLY ALL OF THAT REMAINING CRUDE OIL BURNED AWAY.  WE PICKED UP THE LITTLE BIT OF RESIDUE THAT REMAINED WITH A BACK-HOE, AND SHOVELS AND PLACED IT WITH THE BURN-PIT RESIDUE ON XXX THE OIL WELL LOCATION.  OUR DRIVERS WILL BE EXPECTED TO USE BETTER JUDGEMENT IN DETERMINING THE CONDITION OF THE ROADS BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO LOAD AND MOVE OIL FROM FIELD LOCATIONS.

THIS ARRANGEMENT WAS BELIEVED TO HAVE EFFECTIVELY BLOCKED AND BRACED THE PRODUCTS. (2) AT THE FOURTH PICK-UP LOCATION, THE DRUVER DISCOVERED THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WAS CALLED IN TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN UP THE DISCHARGE.  THE VEHICLE WAS RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL AND THE MP VACUUM TRUCK SERVICE WAS EMPLOYED TO DECONTAMINATE THE EQUIPMENT. (3) INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER'S INTERIOR REVELED THAT THE FORKLIFT (DURING THE INITIAL LOADING OPERATION) HAD APPARENTLY FRACTURED A WEAK AREA IN THE FLOOR'S HARDWOOD PLANKING, THEREBY CAUSING A SHARP POINTED PIECE OF FLOORING TO ELEVATE ABOVE THE SURFACE.  THIS DAMAGE WAS NOT NOTICED BY THE DRIVER, BUT IS BELIEVED TO HAVE PUNCTURED THE DRUM DURING LOAD SHIFT CREATED BY SEVERAL MILES OF ROUGH ROADWAY TRAVEL. (4) DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT INSIDE OF VAN BEFORE AND AFTER LOADING HAZ MAT THEREON.

DRUING THE MORNING SITE WALK, A WHITE SPOT UNDERNEATH THE FRONT PASSENGER SIDE OF THE STRAIGHT TRUCK BAX WAS NOTICED.  TAKING A CLOSER LOOK TO ASCERTAIN WHERE THE SPOT ORIGINATED FROM,  IT WAS NOTED THAT MATERAIL WAS LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOOR BOARDS IN THAT SAME AREA AT THE RATE OF A VERY SLOW DRIP.  THE MANIFEST WAS USED TO IDENTIFY WHAT WAS ON THE VEHICLE TO DETERMINE THAT AN IMMEDIATE HAZARD WAS NOT PRESENT ALONG WITH TAKING THE PH WHICH SHOWED TO BE 0-1 AND MONITORING THE LEL VAPORS AROUND THE VEHICLE WAS BACKED UP TO THE LOADING DOCK WHICH HAD BEEN PREPARED BY LAYING DOWN 6 MIL. POLY AND AN ABSORBENT DIKE.  THE GENERAL AREA WAS IDENTIFIED AND ONCE AGAIN THE MANIFEST WAS CHECKED TO MAKE A SECOND CHECK FOR ANY IMMEDIATE HAZARD.  NEXT THE VEHICLE WAS UNLOADED UNTIL THE CORRECT CONTAINER WAS LOCATED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING FROM A LOOSE BUNG CAP ON THE SIDE LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM END.  IT IS VERY POSSIBLE THAT THE PAINT FROM THE RECONDITIONING PLANT KEPT THE BUNG FROM LEAKING PRIOR TO THAT TIME ALONG WITH MAKING IT SEEM SECURE WHEN CHECKED BY HAND. ON MARCH 12, 1991 A RICH-HILL TRANSPORTATION, INC.  DRIVER DELIVERED A LOAD (6100 GALLONS) OF #6 FUEL OIL TO JAMES RIVER CORP. (REIGEL DIVISION)- WARREN GLEN, NEW JERSEY.  UPON DELIVERY THE DRIVER HOOKED UP THE LINES TO BEGIN TO PUMP OFF.  THE DRIVER ERROR WAS THAT HE FORGOT TO OPEN THE VENT ON THE TRAILER.  WHEN HE STARTED TO PUMP THE TANK WAS SUCKED IN AND MADE A CRACK RELEASING SOME PRODUCT (APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS).   IMMEDIATELY THE DRIVER MADE A DIKE SO THE PRODUCT WOULD NOT SPREAD AND QUICKLY FINISHED PUMPING OFF THE PRODUCT AS SAFELY AS POSSIBLE. DUE TO THE QUICK DRIVER REPONSE A VERY MINIMAL AMOUNT WAS LOST. IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE OFFICE A RICH-HIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS SENT OUT FINISHING THE BALANCE OF THE CLEANUP. TO DATE WE ARE WAITING FOR S & W WASTE-KEARNY, NEW JERSEY TO PICK UP THE CONTAMINATED SOIL THAT WAS CLEANED UP BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW.  THE SPILL WAS ATTRIBUTED TO DRIVER ERROR BUT THIS IS THE ONLY ACCIDENT OR SPILL THIS PARTICULAR DRIVER HAD HAD IN OVER 20 YEARS WITH RICH-HIL TRANSPORTATION, INC.

drum was not damaged when it was put on delivery trlr 9772k on 3/28/91. when the driver arrived at sns in waldoboro, me., he noticed a black grease-like substance in the back of his trailer.  he initially thought it was some kind of grease leaking from a roto-tiller sitting by the drum of acid. the st. j. driver, jim stuart, and the receiver at sns picked up the drum by the handles on top and from a pin-hole in the re-inforceed rim around the bottom of the drum.  a substance called "corncob"  was sprinkled on the spillage on the sns dock and in the back of the st. j. trailer. the driver then called the gardiner st. j. terminal.  he was instructed to keep everyone away from the spill.  i then notified chemtrec and the waldoboro fire department.  the waldoboro fire dept., came immediately and cleaned up the spilled material, placing it in a plastic bag and left the plastic bag at sns.  i made arrangements with clean harbors in portland, me., to go the following day and overpack the leaking drum in a 30-gal. kilm pack for return to the shipper and top pick up the bag of "hazardous material" to be taken to clean harbors in braintree, ma., for incineration.  back at the terminal we inspected the trailer to see if the puncture occurred because of something in the trailer.  the trailer floor was in good condition, no sharp fragments that could have caused a puncture.  the acid was in a re-usable drum and, in my opinion, there was some type of failure in the drum itself that caused the spill.

WHILE UNLOADING THE ASSIGNED PERSON TELLS OUR DRIVER THAT HE HAD TO TEND TO OTHER DUTIES AND WILL RETURN BEFORE UNLOADING IS COMPLETE. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: INSTRUCT ALL DRIVERS TO SHUT DOWN UNLOADING WHEN NO ONE IS WATCHING FILLING OF STORAGE TANK.

TWO EMPLOYEES OF WASTE RESEARCH & RECLAMATION CO., INC. (WRR) WERE FILLING CHICAGO NW RAILCAR #NATX-22603 WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (UN 1993) FROM WRR TANKER #T-12 AT WRR'S LEASED ALTOONA FAIL SPUR. BECAUSE OF LOADER ERROR, THE RAILCAR WAS OVERFILLED BY 200 GALLONS AT 1345.  ASSISTANCE WAS SUMMONED BY EMERGENCY PHONE AT LOCATION (30 FEET WAWAY) AND CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP STARTED WITH EQUIPMENT AND MATERIALS FROM DEDICATED SPILL TRAILER (20 FEET AWAY).  WARNING SIGNS WERE SET PRIOR TO LOADING.  AT 1400 ASSISTANCE ARRIVED, UP TO 16 WRR EMPLOYEES INVOLVED, OF THOSE 11 ARE FIRE BRIGADE MEMBERS (VOLUNTEER FIREMEN).  BECAUSE OF FAVORABLE CONDITIONS FOR PREVENTING IGNITION, NO ADDITIONAL FIRE DEPARTMENT ASSISTANCE WAS DEEMED NECESSARY.  AT 1405 THE TRAINMASTER WAS INFORMED.  AT 1407 THE STATE DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES (DNR) WAS NOTIFIED.  AT 1420 STATE DNR OFFICER ARRIVED.  HE WAS SATISFIED WITH THE ACTIONS, TAKEN.  AT 1437 STATE DIV. OF EMERGENCY GOVERNMENT NOTIFIED.  AT 1600 SPILL CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED.  SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN.  WRR SCP'S HAVE BEEN CHANGED TO PREVENT REPEAT OF SPILL.

ON 4/20/91 A LOADER PICKED UP A CASE OF SULFURIC ACID WHICH UNKNOWN TO HIM, CONTAINED A BROKEN BOTTLE.  HE PLACED THE CASE ON TOP OF A PALLET AT A HEIGHT OF 5-6 FEET; THE ACID SPILLED FROM THE CASE AND HIT HIS FACE, NECK, TORSO, ARMS AND LEG.  HE IMMEDIATELY RAN TO THE SHOWER.  FOLLOWING CONTINOUS WASHING, A TEAM LEADER TOOK HIM TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT OF 2ND & 3RD DEGREE BURNS. THE LOADER HAD BEEN TRAINED IN THE PROPER METHOD FOR HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND KNEW NOT TO PUT A CASE AT THAT HEIGHT.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING WAS PROVIDED TO ALL TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEES AT THE QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING ON 3/23/91.  AN UPDATE OF THE ANNUAL HAZ. MAT. TRAINING IS SCHEDULED FOR 6/22/91.

DRIVER WAS PUMPING #4 OIL INTO CUSTOMER STORAGE.  THE UNLOADING SITE IS CONSISTING OF TWO 30,000 GALLON ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANKS THAT ARE FED BY ONE LINE AND CONTROLLED BY A CROSS OVER VALVE.  THE TANK THAT THE DRIVER UNLOADED INTO WAS FULL AND THE CROSS OVER VALVE HAD NOT BEEN CHANGED OVER TO THE OTHER TANK BY THE CUSTOMER WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AND STARTED TO UNLOAD.  THE #4 OIL WENT OUT OF THE VENT PIPE ON THE FULL STORAGE TANK INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA THAT SURROUNDED THE TANKS.  THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN HIS EQUIPMENT AND THIS COMPANY'S CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WENT TO THE AREA AND CLEANED THE PRODUCTS UP AND DISPOSED OF SAME.  FUTURE SHIPMENTS TO THIS CUSTOMER WILL BE DONE DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS ONLY SO AS TO DO AWAY WITH THIS TYPE OF PROBLEM.

column168: ON MARCH 25, 1991 OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO CHA'S MOBILE ON RIGGS ROAD, CHILLUM, MD.  THE DEALER ORDERED TOO MUCH GAS AND COULD NOT HOLD THE WHOLE LOAD.  THE DRIVER FILLED UP THE SUPER GAS TANK AND WHEN IT WAS FULL IT SEEMED LIKE IT HAD A LOT OF PRESSURE BUILDUP AND GAS CAME UP AROUND THE FITTING THAT THE DRIVER HAD LOCKED ON THE FILL. THE DRIVER HAD THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER SHUT OFF AND GAS STILL OOZED OUT AROUND THE LOCK ON THE FITTING AND UP IN THE VAPOR HOSE.  THE DRIVER SPILLED AROUND 25 TO 30 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO CONTAIN IT THE BEST THAT HE COULD.  SOME OF THE GAS WENT DOWN A HOLE IN WHICH THE DEALER SAID THAT IT WAS GOING INTO A HOLDING TANK UNDERGROUND.  THE DEALER TOLD THE DRIVER THAT THERE WAS NOTHING ELSE THAT HE COULD DO.  AFTER THE DRIVER LEFT THE DEALER WASHED DOWN THE LOT WITH WATER WHICH ALSO WENT INTO THE HOLDING TANK.  WHEN THE DEALER WASHED DOWN THE LOT WITH WATER SOME OF THE WATER WENT THROUGH THE HOLES IN THE CURBING AND THROUGH SOME OF THE DIRT TO THE HOLDING TANK.  THE DEALER CALLED THE MAIN HEADQUARTERS AT MOBIL IN WHICH THEY TOLD CHA'S MOBIL TO CALL THE CONTRACTOR TO COME OUT AND PUMP THE HOLDING TANK OUT.  THE CONTRACTOR IN TURN CALLED THE FIRE MARSHALL.  TRI COUNTY INDUSTRIES CAME OUT AND PUMPED THE HOLDING TANK 0UT.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING IN AN OVERHEAD TANK WHEN THE TANK OVERFLOWED.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO TURN SAFETY SWITCH ON PROPERLY TO SOUND AN ALARM IN CASE OF OVERFILL.  HE WAS STANDING BY THE VALVES WHEN SPILL OCCURRED AND IMMEDIATELY SHUT VALVES.  THE DRIVER WAS TALKED TO ABOUT THE INCIDENT AND WAS DISCIPLINED.

column168: AT 1000 ON MARCH 26, 1991 I WAS SUMMONEDED TO THE DOCK ARE BY A DRIVE, WHO INFORMED ME THERE WERE BAGS OF A CUSTOMER'S PRODUCT WHICH WERE TORN OPEN. THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AS FRUIT FUNGICIDE BY USE OF THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS AND PACKING SLIP.  THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED BY THIS CON-WAY OFFICE TO RECEIVE INSTRUCTIONS ON PROPER HANDLING.  ONCE THOSE INSTRUCTIONS WERE RECEIVED, THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER.  THE BAGS AND CARTON WERE TORN IN MANNER WHICH WOULD INDICATE THEY WERE RUBBED ALONG THE TRAILER WALL WHILE BEING LOADED.  THE ONLY RECOMMEDATION I WOULD MAKE TO AVOID THIS SITUATION WOULD BE TO USE MORE CAR IN HANDLING.

OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING ALONG ROUTE 118 WHEN IT WAS STOPPED BY A LOCAL POLICE OFFICER FOR TRAVELING ON A RESTRICTED ROAD.  THE OFFICER NOTICED A "DRIP" FROM THE BACK DOOR.  THE VAN DOORS WERE ESTIMATED OPENED AND REVEALED A LID ON A DRUM HAD COME AJAR ONE ROW IN ROM THE BACK.  LUZERNE COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE DALLAS TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPT.  SPILL PADS WERE USED TO WIPE DOWN THE SIDES OF THE DRUM AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, THE DRIPS ON THE GROUND WERE SCOOPED UP WITH A SHOVEL AND PLACED IN THE OVERPACK DRUM THAT IS CARRIED ON OUR VEHICLE. THE CONTAINER WITH THE LID AJAR WAS RESEALED AND PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK DRUM WITH THE SPILL PADS AND THE SOIL.  THE LOAD CONTINUED TO ITS DESTINATION ECOLOTEC, INC. 636 N IRWIN STREET, DAYTON OH, 45403.  WHEN THE TRAILER RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL IN FREEHOLD, N.J. IT WAS THOROUGHLY WASHED WITH SOAP AND WATER.

AT POINT OF DELIVERY ONE PALLET SHOWED VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE FROM AN INTERNALLY STACKED CASE.  THE LEAKING CASE WAS REMOVED AND OPENED FINDING 1 BOTTLE IN SAID CASE HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP DUE TO POOR PACKAGING.  THE BOTTLE LEAKING WAS REPACKAGED.  TRRAILER WAS WASHED DOWN (WITH WATER) TILL PH WAS 7 ON NEUTRAL.

THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE DRIVER WAS REFILLING A PROPANE FORKLIFT CYLINDER.  THE ACME SECTON ON FILLER VALVE BROKE AND WEDGED IN THE FILLER VALVE ON HOSE THUS ALLOWING AN UNRESTRICTED FLOW OF GAS WHICH IMMEDIATELY ACTIVATED THE EXCESS INTERNAL FLOW VALVE ON TRUCK (SHUTTING DOWN).  THE AMOUNT OF GAS ESCAPED WAS THE CONTENT OF THE HOSE AND PIPES TO INTERNAL VALVE. THE EXPLOSION AND FIRE OCCURRED WHEN GAS ENTERED THE BUILDING AND IGNITED BY SOME SOURCE. THE HOSE, METER AND VALVES WERE DESTROYED BY THE FIRE.  TRUCK WAS MOVED EVACUATED AND TOWED TO OFFICE COMPOUND FOR SUBSEQUENT REPAIRS.

GATX 17218 WAS FOUND LEAKING DURING INSPECTION OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD DELIVERY.  THIS TANK IS INSULATED, JACKETED AND RUBBER LINED. LEAK WAS COMING THROUGH THE JACKET NEAR THE BRAKE CYLINDER RESERVOIR AND BRAKE CYLINDER BRACKETS.  THE HOLES IN JACKET WERE PLUGGED USING WOODEN PLUGS WHICH ALMOST STOPPED THE FLOW.  A PLASTIC SHEET WAS ATTACHED TO RAILCAR AND IT SERVED LIKE A DIAPER TO CATCH LEAKAGE.  RAILCAR WAS MOVED FROM RECEIVING YARD TRACK 1503 TO THE OLD YARD WHERE IT WAS MORE ACCESSIBLE.  LOAD WAS TRANSLOADED INTO 4 STAINLESS STEEL TANK TRAILERS SUPPLIED BY BULK TRANSPORTATION.  THE WOOD PLUGS WERE REMOVED & THE PRODUCT TRAPPED BETWEEN THE JACKET & THE SHELL WAS DRAINED INTO A PLASTIC BARREL.  THE SPILLAGE IN THE RECEIVING YARD WAS NEUTRALIZED USING CAUSTIC SODA & THEN DILUTED WITH WATER.  CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL DISPOSAL OF MONTCLAIR, CALIFORNIA ASSISTED WITH THIS CLEANUP.

column168: I, KAREN NICHOLS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR FOR ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OHIO  45177, INVESTIGATED AN ODOR ON THE MAIN DECK OF OUR AIRCRAFT 904AX (DC-9).  ON MARCH 9, 1991 AT APPROX. 01:54 HRS. AFTER UNLOADING AIRCRAFT IN LEVEL B PROTECTION, THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS FOUND TO BE PAINT RELATED MATERIALS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH ORIENTATION ARROWS SHOWING PROPER OPRIENTATION.  THE FIBREBOARD BOX HAD NO HAZARD MARKING OR LABELS ON IT.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX, PACKED IN STYROFOAM PEANUTS, WERE 3 SQUARE, 1 GALLON METAL CANS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, 2 METAL "PAINT TYPE" CANS WITH FRICTION CLOSURES (CAPACITY 1 GALLON EACH).  1-2QT. METAL CAN WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THE 2 SQUARE METAL CAN APPEARED TO BE THE ONE THAT LEAKED.  IT CONTAINED ACRYLIC URETHANE HARDENER ACCELERATOR.  THE METAL CAN APEARED TO HAVE LEAKED APPROX. 1 PINT.  THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABLES ON ANY OF THE METAL CANS EXCEPT FOR AN NFPA LABEL ON THE PAINT TYPE CANS.  HEALTH RATING OF 2, FLAMMABILITY OF 3, REACTIVITY 0.  THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD IN OUR HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  IT WILL BE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION, VIA TRUCK, IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA.

column168: RE: LEAKING TANK CARS, GATX 99402 AND ACFX 81666 WASTE OIL WITH SOLIDS, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. ON MARCH 1, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, RF&P CONTROL CENTER RECEIVED INFORMATIRON FROM A HANOVER COUNTY DEPUTY SHERIFF THAT TANK CAR GATX 99402 APPEARED TO BE LEAKING ITS CONTENTS WHEN IT PASSED HIS LOCATION IN ASHLAND, VIRGINIA.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE TANK CAR WAS IN SOUTHBOUND TRAIN CO. 413 AND WAS EXPECTED TO ARRIVE ACCA YARD AROUND 1300 HOURS. MR. W. E. PRICE, JR., ASSISTANT TRANSPORTATION MANAGER FOR RF&P, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE NOTIFIED MR. WILLIAM H. OERTLY.  DISTRICT INSPECTOR OF AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, AT 1210 HOURS.  MR. OERTLY ADVISED THAT HE WOULD RESPOND TO ACCA YARD TO REPAIR THE TANK CAR. WHEN RF&P TRAIN NO. R413 ARRIVED ACCA AT 1300 HOURS. IT WAS YARDED IN NO. 3 NORTH YARD TRACK AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WERE TWO TANK CARS LEAKING.  GATX 99402 AND ACFX 81666 BOTH WERE SHIPPED BY SAFETY KLEEN CORPORATION OF PHILADELPHIA, PENNSYLVANIA, AND BOTH CONTAINED WASTE OIL WITH SOLIDS.  WHEN AN INSPECTION WAS MADE BY MR. OERTLY ON CAR GATX 99402, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKING AROUND THE ROD OF THE TOP-OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS MISSING, ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO SLOSH OUT AROUND THE ROD ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  ALSO, THE NUT WHICH HOLDS THE PACKING IN PLACE AROUND THE ROD WAS FROZEN IN PLACE AND COULD NOT BE REMOVED.  MR. OERTLY WAS ABLE TO FORCE THE PACKING DOWN AROUND THE ROD AND SECURE THE OPENING. TANK CAR ACFX 81666 WAS FOUND TO HAVE A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET WHICH ALLOWED OIL TO SLOSH OUT AROUND THE COVER.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED IN THE MANWAY AND THE COVER SECURED.  REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED TO BOTH TANKS AT 1345 HOURS AND THE CARS WERE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE SOUTHBOUND IN CSXT TRAIN R413.  IT WAS FELT THAT BOTH PROBLEMS HAD EXISTED WHEN THE CARS WERE SHIPPED AND CARS SHOULD HAVE BEEN REPAIRED BY THE SHIPPER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1413 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, SAFETY KLEEN CORPORATION.  MR. PAUL PETERSON, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER FOR SAFETY KLEEN, CALLED BACK AT 1435 HOURS AND WAS ADVISED OF THE LEAKING TANK CARS AND THE REPAIRS.

column168: RE: LEAKING TANK CAR GATX 39040 N-METHYL PYRROLIDONE COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID N.O.S. ON MARCH 11, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HOURS, ACCA YARD ASSIGNMENT AC-3 REPORTED THAT TANK CAR GATX 39040 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM FITTING OF THE CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS PROMPTLY ISOLATED ON NO. 20 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1505 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER. BASF CORPORATION, GEISMER, LOUISIANA.  MR. WILLIAM J. OERTLY, DISTRICT INSPECTOR OF AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, WAS NOTIFIED AT 1508 HOURS.  MR. OERTLY ADVISED THAT HE WOULD RESPOND TO ACCA YARD TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE. THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AT 1520 HOURS AND FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM AROUND THE THREADED FITTING ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE DRIPPING AT A VERY SLOW RATE AND NO PONDING OR RUNOFF WAS DETECTED. AFTER TELEPHONE DISCUSSION WITH MR. JOE STAFANON, EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST FOR BASF CORPORATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT POSSIBLY THE TOP-OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT SEALED PROPERLY ALONG WITH THE BOTTOM FITTING NOT BEING PROPERLY TIGHTENED. MR. OERTLY INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THAT TO BE THE PROBLEM.  AFTER RESEATING THE VALVE, AND TIGHTENING THE BOTTOM FITTING, THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 1700 HOURS. TANK CAR GATX 39040 WAS RETURNED TO RAIL SERVICE AT 1715 HOURS. THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THAT THE CONSIGNEE, DUPONT, E. I. DENEMOURS OF RICHMOND, VIRGINIA, BE ALLOWED TO INSPECT THE CAR.  MR. LARRY L. DAVIS, CHIEF OF SPRUANCE EMERGENCY SERVICES, RESPONDED AT 1800 HOURS.  INSPECTION WAS MADE AT 1805 HOURS AND BOTTOM FITTINGS WERE FOUND TO BE DRY WITH NO SIGN OF LEAKAGE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings; Vent
column168: ON MONDAY, MARCH 18,1991, AT APPROXIMATLEY 1450 HOURS, ACCA YARD ASSIGNEMENT AR-2 DISCOVERED TANK CAR GATX 41052 LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO THE YARDMASTER AND THE CAR WAS PLACED IN NO. 20 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD WHERE IT WAS ISOLATED UNTIL REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. MR. T. W. GRUBBS, SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE TANK CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING AND HE WENT TO NO. 20 TRACK TO INSPECT THE TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS NOT LEAKING ON HIS ARRIVAL, BUT IT HAD BEEN LEAKING WHEN IN MOTION FROM AROUND THE AREA OF THE FITTINGS WHICH CONTAIN THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  MR. GRUBBS CONTANCTED WILLIAM J. OERTLY, JR., DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, AT 1535 HOURS, AND MR. OERTLY ADVISED THAT HE WOULD RESPOND TO ACCA YARD TO REPAIR THE TANK CAR.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1548 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, TEXASGULF INCORPORATED, OF P. O. BOX 48, AURORA, NORTH CAROLINA 27806.  MR. OERTLY ARRVIED AT 1610 HOURS, AND WHEN AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE TANK CAR, THE CAUSE FOR THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND REPAIRS WERE COMPLATED AT 1645 HOURS.  THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED INTO RAIL SERVICE AT 1700 HOURS.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE, MR. FRED ADAMS, TRAFFIC SUPERVISOR FOR TEXASGULF INCORPORATED, CALLED BACK AT 1715 HOURS AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED.

column168: I BENJAMIN TAYLOR, HM COORD, FOR ABX AIR, INC.  RECEIVED A CALL FROM SORT SUPERVISOR  01:22 AM ADVISING THAT HE HAD A PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING AND HAD AN ODOR OF KEROSENE OR LIGHTER FLUID.  UPON ARRIVING, MY SPILL PARTNER AND I FOUND A PACKAGE THAT WAS STAINED AND I DETECTED AN ODOR OF GASOLINE.  WE IMMEDIATELY REMOVED THAT PACKAGE TO A LOCATION WHERE A MORE THOROUGH INSPECTION COULD BE MADE.  THE OUTER MOST PACKAGE WAS BROWN WRAPPING PAPER - THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE PACKAGE AND THE WAYBILL DID NOT GIVE A DESCRIPTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS REVEALED A GASOLINE POWERED ENGINE, AND AFTER REMOVING THE FUEL TANK CAP IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK WAS APPROXIMATELY 3/4 FULL. THE FUEL TANK WAS A I GAL CAPACITY.  WE SECURED THE SHIPMENT IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL FEDERAL AUTHORITIES COULD TAKE THEIR PICTURES AND FILE THEIR REPORTS  WHEN THE SHIPMENT IS RELEASED IT WILL BE TRANSPORTED VIA HIGHWAY IN FULL COMPLIANCE WITH TITLE 49 CFR.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY UP MANAGER OF CAR MAINTENANCE (JIM OSBURN) THAT TANK CAR RAIX 2716 HAD A STAIN ON THE SIDE INDICATING A POSSIBLE LEAK.  OSBURN INSPECTED THE TANK AND FOUND THAT THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND HAD ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT AND DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  OSBURN SECURED THE BOLTS AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT.  UNION CARBIDE CHEMICAL (TAFT, LA) WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM.

UPON INSPECTION OF A PACKAGE EMITTING A STRONG ODOR, THE CAN WAS PACKED ON IT'S SIDE AND THE LID WAS LOOSE AND DENTED. THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO UPS PROCEDURES, AND A DAMAGED INSPECTION REPORT FILED, BY PSC KATHY PIRRWITZ.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AS DRIVER WAS PRESSURIZING TANK FOR OFF LOADING, HE NOTICED SPRAY COMING FROM DOME COVER.  HE CUT AIR PRESSURE AND FLUSHED TRAILER WITH WATER IN OUR PIT AREA. ALL SPILLAGE WAS RECOVERED.  THE DRIVER HAD PROPERLY SECURED THE DOME COVER BUT THERE WAS A FAILURE OF THE DOME SECURING BOLT. MAINTENANCE REPLACED THE DOME BOLT.  LOAD WAS OFF LOADED.  DRIVERS TO EXAMINE BOLTS AND THREADS TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE SOUND AND IN GOOD WORKING ORDER.  NRC NUMBER 65158 3-25-91

column18: P O BOX 1277 703 S GEORGE ST
column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AND THE CAP CAME OFF THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TANK AND APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF FUEL ESCAPED.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE CONCRETE SURFACE AND WAS CLEANED UP UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE FAYETTEVILLE HAZ-MAT TEAM. (REPORT #30491).
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: COLE ENTERPRISES ASSOCIATE WAS UNLOADING A 1966 BUTLER TANKER (VIN# 4432, ME REG. T33834) INTO A UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (MAINE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION FACILITY REGISTRATION NUMBER: 6877, INSTALLED 9/26/86, 10,000 GAL. GALVANIZED STEEL).  DURING UNLOADING THE UNDERGROUND TANK FILLED AND 55 GALLONS RAN OFF ONTO THE SNOW PACKED DRIVEWAY.  MR. KEITH ALLEN, AT THE MAINE D.E.P. WAS CALLED AND INSTRUCTED THE PRESQUE ISLE TERMINAL MANAGER TO ABSORB WHAT EVER POSSIBLE, AND CLEAN UP THE RUN-OFF AS THE SNOW MELTED IN THE SPRING.  DELMONT WOOD & SONS, INC. (GENERAL CONTRACTOR & BULLDOZER WORK) WERE HIRED TO REMOVE THE RUN OFF AS THE SNOW MELTED.  THE UNTIMELENESS OF THIS REPORT IS BECAUSE PRIOR TO THE ACTUAL CLEAN UP, COLE ENTERPRISES ORIGINALLY THOUGHT TO HAVE LOST ONLY 10 GALLONS.  THIS WAS PROVEN OTHERWISE WHEN THE CLEAN-UP BILLS WERE RECEIVED IN JUNE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 03/16/91 (0410 HOURS), SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT (SSA/HM) DON LOW WAS NOTIFIED THAT TWO TANK CARS, UTLX 12017 AND UTLX 13886, HAD BEEN DERAILED (WEST END, SOUTH LEAD).  SSA/HM LOW'S INSPECTION OF TANK CAR UTLX 12017 DETERMINED THAT THREE SWING BOLTS WERE FINGER TIGHT WHICH ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF ACID TO LEAK FROM THE MANWAY.  SSA/HM LOW SECURED THE SWING BOLTS WHICH STOPPED LEAK.
